{ @@HeaderStart@@Sethuraman's 1.e4 Part 2: a Lifetime Repertoire@@HeaderEnd@@   The “1. e4 Saga” continues...    Hello, friends from all over the Chess World! Welcome to my second part of 1. e4. This is Grandmaster S.P. Sethuraman and I am back with my deadliest novelties and roaring analysis with breezy and entertaining comments. Hope you guys relished Part-1 of this series which focused on the Petroff, Scotch & others, and now we are continuing the journey ahead with the Sicilians, French, and Caro Kann. So, I can already feel the excitement among you when you hear the names: 'Sicilian, French and Caro Kann.' I can guess that your first question will be whether I am going to steer the wheel into semipopular directions like the Rosolimo or dive into the ocean of the killer Open Sicilians. We are diving headfirst into the principled Open Sicilians battles, the highly fashionable and aggressive Tal Variation against the Caro Kann, and the dangerous 3. Nc3 against the French, which could lead to lines such as the Rubinstein, Steinitz, or Winawer variations. So, the lines I've chosen contain a lot of atom bombs, waiting to burst.     As they say, the 1. b3 boys belong to the Cowboy clan. I was wondering, what do we call ourselves who play 1.e4 -? It is indeed a million-dollar Question, :@@EndBracket@@ and perhaps the one identity which comes to my mind right now is the Wolf Pack. :@@EndBracket@@ We can take pride in calling ourselves, The Wolf Pack as they are intelligent and hunt together. So, let’s begin to hunt by playing 1. e4!    My notable achievements      I have a Fide Rating of 2644 @@StartBracket@@My best so far is 2672@@EndBracket@@.   I have won the Asian Championship in the year 2016.  I am a member of the historic bronze-winning Indian team at the Tromso Olympiad 2014.   And in the year 2020, I was euphoric to venture on a new role as an author and I wrote a book on the two main Sicilians - Taimanov and Najdorf from the White side for Thinkers Publishing.   So, I already have ample experience in taming the Sicilians. And then my journey as an author continues in Chessable as you are now holding my fourth course. I hope my courses and books have made a huge impact on the students to improve their understanding and get into the mind of how a Grandmaster analyses his openings and I can assure you that this course which you are holding right now is one of my best works and I am pretty confident that it will make a big name.   Among my fellow compatriots and peers, I have always made a huge impression on them for my opening preparation and known to be a deadly 1. e4 player. It was really mellifluous to receive appreciation of my opening work from the former World Champion, my chess hero, and ageless Vishy Anand himself, who quoted the following words in the foreword of my book on 1. e4 against the Nadjtorf and Taimanov. So here it goes.”   In his own words:  @@StartBlockQuote@@I got to know Sethu more closely a few years back when we trained together a few times. I found him to be meticulous in his preparation and especially at home in complex positions “-Vishy Anand.   @@EndBlockQuote@@I'm happy to have trained with the World Champion himself in a few instances, and it has immensely helped me to widen my analytical skills. And spilling some secrets here, we did check some 1. e4 in our training sessions. Perhaps this course might have some analysis from it. Who knows?!  @@HeaderStart@@Overview of the Course@@HeaderEnd@@    Part 2 consists of 22 mind-blowing Chapters along with 14 instructive model games, and 130 key training exercises. It’s not only about the opening moves, we also learn a lot of things along the way like how to use a space advantage, the position of your pieces, slow poison sacrifices, concrete calculation, and more.     A@@EndBracket@@ Openings Section     Chapter 1:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5    2.Nf3  Sidelines for Black like  2...b6  ,   2...Qc7  ,   2...Qa5  and so on.    Chapter 2 will cover the O' Kelly line with   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  a6   & the Nimzowitsch Defense with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nf6  .    Chapter 3 will slowly steer the wheel towards the Main Sicilians starting with   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  and here, of course, we go for the open Sicilians with  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  and in this chapter, we will be dealing the Grivas Siclian after  4...Qb6  .    Chapter 4: Kalashnikov and Sveshnikov, the two relative openings arising from 2...Nc6 will be focused in-depth here. Against Kalashnikov that is   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  5.Nb5  d6  I have suggested the main plan with c4 and against the Sveshnikov we hop on to  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  6.Ndb5  d6  7.Nd5!?  which is the trendy, new system that became extremely popular after the World Championship match between Caruana and Carlsen. So, we go for the fashionable stuff which gives a fresh vibe rather than the long-forced lines with  7.Bg5  a6  8.Na3  b5  .    Chapter 5: The Four Horsemen, or The Four Knights Sicilian which can arise from either   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e6   or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  Nc6  .  This tabiya is really heating up at the top level after the thumping win of Anish Giri against Caruana in the recent Candidates 2021 and here we will go with the principled mainline with  6.Nxc6  bxc6  7.e5  stuff, operating in the center and gaining space.    Chapter 6: The Paulsen Variation:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  a6  ,  I recommend the principled main line with  5.Bd3  followed by c4-Nc3 setups. And space advantage plays a big role here as well and it leads to pleasant positions for White. I have employed this system regularly in my tournament practice and once again fell in love with it while presenting it here.    Chapter 7:  Taimanov & Others:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nc6  5.Nc3  Qc7  5...d6 and 5...a6 are also probed in greater depth.   Against  5...d6  comes a swashbuckling  6.g4  aiming for aggressive positions.   Against  5...a6  I found a rare and interesting direction with  6.Bf4  .   Generally the mainline there is  6.Nxc6  bxc6  7.Bd3  as suggested in the book of Parimarjan Negi.  and this move 6. Bf4 is quite lucid which keeps control over the dark squares.   So coming back to main Taimanov with  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qc7  6.Be3  a6  ,  here comes the voguish  7.g4   7.Qf3   and  7.Qd2  are the two main moves and the former is in my book Beating the Nadjtorf and Taimanov.  This move  7.g4  is stylish and it is really heating up as when I was about to finish this course, the former World Champion Vishy Anand used it to beat Van Forest, Jordan in Grand chess Tour, Croatia. It is highly dangerous for Black and contains a lot of new ideas.  ()  Chapter 8: covers the Classical Sicilian which once again can arise from two different move orders like   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  Nc6   or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  Nc6  . And my suggestion is the principled  6.Bg5  ,  the Ritcher Rauzer Attack which is considered to be the most grievous response against the Classical Sicilian and against  6...e6  I have come up with the modern  7.Qd3  which is exuberant and contains a lot of fresh directions/ideas.    Chapter 9: Keres Attack against the Scheveningen:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e6  (and can also come via)   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e6  and here we go with the thumping  6.g4  known as the Keres Attack with a killer instinct.    Chapter 10: The Dragon! The name sounds exciting, doesn't it? I saw a tweet of Mr. Anish Giri which said, more than the opening, the impressive cool name lured him to make a course on Dragon, Lol. :P  Here we will venture with all the three dragons:   The Accelerated Dragon:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  g6    The Hyper Accelerated Dragon:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  g6  which will transpose to the territory of the Acc. Dragon after  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Bg7  5.c4    and the Main Dragon:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  g6  and there is Dragadorf as well after  6.Be3  a6  instead of 6...Bg7. Dragadorf = Sicilian Dragon + Sicilian Najdorf, combining characteristics of both the Dragon and the Najdorf. Against the Accelerated Dragon, we approach with Maroczy Bind with c4 systems which is rock solid.    Chapter 11: Najdorf Sidelines on Move 5: after   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  will be dealt and as well combined with some of Najdorf lines. Against the Najdorf,  5...a6  after much deliberation, I took up the courage to dive into the ocean of razor-sharp lines with the lethal  6.Bg5  ,  the acid test for Black and the one which scares people playing Najdorf.   So in this chapter, we will check 6...Nbd7 and 6...e6 7.f4 b5 the Polugaevesky line. So for  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nbd7  we opt for Fischer's favorite square for the Bishop, that is  7.Bc4   and against  6...e6  7.f4  Nbd7  ,  the Gelfand line we head to  8.Qe2  system preparing for e5 breaks.    Chapter 12: Najdorf Poisoned Pawn Variations:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bg5  Qb6   and  6...h6  Bh4  Qb6  systems will be focused on.   Against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qb6  we prefer  7.Nb3   and against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/6B1/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...h6  7.Bh4  Qb6  we opt for the  8.a3  system. And there is a spoiler alert here as we have a spectacular Queen sacrifice in one of the lines.    Chapter 13: Najdorf Mainline:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bg5  e6  7.f4  Be7  , the Classical Mainline which was the main suggestion of Anish Giri in his Chessable course. And here we go with the setup of Qf3, O-O-O and g4. Obviously, I have checked the Twitter King's course and have improved on that. So, then we come to an end of the Open Sicilians.    Chapter 14: Now we arrive at the Caro Kann, where we steer into the Advanced variation with   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  and here both 3...c5 and 3...Bf5 moves have been covered in this chapter itself. Against  3...c5  we opt for  4.Nf3  cxd4  5.Nxd4  Nc6  6.Nxc6  and I have found some nice improvements over Erwin's Chessable course.   The same applies to well for @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3pP3/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bf5  where we probe into the highly creative  4.h4  ,  the Tal Variation. Like the magician, the variation is also one of the aggressive responses to the Caro Kann.    Chapter 15: Comes the French and yes no more 3. Nd2 business, as we probe into the mainline with   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  and here we will be focusing on the rare and dubious line like  3...a6  ,   3...h6   3...c5   and  3...Nc6  .    Chapter 16: We slowly head to the mainstems of French and here we mainly deal with the Rubenstein which arises after   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  dxe4  4.Nxe4  Nd7  .    Chapter 17-19 will deal with the French Steinitz lines:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.e5  .    Chapter 17: The systems with   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2N1BN2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Be7  and other move 7 Sidelines are scoured in depth.    Chapter 18: The direction with   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2N1BN2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 3 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qb6  is heavily probed.    Chapter 19:   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2N1BN2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...cxd4  stuff is explored.    Chapter 20-22 will consist of the Winawer, divided into three chapters.    Chapter 20: This chapter is about all the sidelines after   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  Bb4  4.e5  like  4...c5  5.a3  Ba5   or  4...b6  & Qd7.   or  4...Ne7  5.a3  Bxc3  6.bxc3  b6  .    Chapter 21: This one's about   @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/1b1PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e5  c5  a3  Bxc3  6.bxc3  Qa5  systems.    Chapter 22: Finally at the end of the course where we deal with the mainline after   @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3pP3/1b1P4/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c5  5.a3  bxc3  6.bxc3  Ne7  and here we go for the kill with  7.Qg4  .   B@@EndBracket@@ Model Games  After the end of the opening Chapter, you guys can browse through the Model games which contain 14 games. There are a lot of my games included in it. So, I had a chance to revisit some of my wonderful and pleasant memories. Apart from that, there are some spectacular correspondence games and top-level human games imbibed in the model games Chapter which corresponds to our opening systems.  C@@EndBracket@@ Training Exercises  I am back to torture the students with 130 training exercises. Just kidding, but many people liked it from my first course, so I thought to bring it back to business. Some are difficult ones; some are easy and some are very easy but the main point is to encounter different critical situations form the course and to train your mind to find answers so that it will register in your mind for a long time. So the positions are arranged in such a away that it contains both positional, strategical and tactical ones jumbled with each other without many hints as in a tournament game no one would tell you the details. Good luck solving them!  D@@EndBracket@@ Quickstarters!  And to start with we have the quick starter guide which will help the viewers to gain a quick insight. It is divided into three parts which will make it convenient for the viewers to browse through.  The first part is on the Sicilian and the second part is on the Caro and the third part on French.  And I would also like to mention the students that there is a prominent feature of important lines marked inside the course which mainly deals with the options having higher chances to occur in a tournament game. So, it is an extremely useful feature available in Chessable apart from many others like the fascinating move trainer technology.  References  Apart from the main tools like Megabase, Twic, Correspondence database, I have gone through various chess books and Chessable courses. To name them a few:  Books:  Parimarjan Negis book on Sicilian/French  Gawain Jones Book on Dragon  Chessable courses:  Anish Giri's course on the Najdorf, French and Dragon  Sam Shankland's course on Classical Sicilian  Wesley's course on  1.e4  part 1 and 2  Erwins course on the Caro Kann  Harikrishna's Course on the Taimanov  Alex Colovic course on Simplified Najdorf  FM Kamil Plichta course on the Four Horsemen  So, these are main chess material I checked out to see what their recommendations are against our main directions.  Uff... That’s a long list and that explains the reason why it took a hell of a lot of time. Good things are always worth the wait I believe and hope this jaw-dropping course will satisfy the people who are eagerly waiting for it. Discussions in the Forum/Feedbacks/ Ideas, First of all, I would like to thank everyone for showing me towering support for all my Chessable courses with some raving reviews and comments. I am always ready for improvements and looking forward to discussing in the forum. So, keep posting them. I love to interact with the wonderful Chessable community in the Forum as every time they surprise me with their interesting suggestions/unexpected ideas. So once again shout out to the lovely people out there supporting my courses and exchanging ideas 😊  Thank you notes:😊  My sincere gratitude to my wonderful parents for always being there and constantly supporting me in all my ventures, my awesome Chessable students for motivating me to do great work, the professional Chessable team always ready to help when you need it, and most importantly the beta testers who did a fantastic job in making this course a quality one. They took a lot of pain to highlight the improvements and I thank them for their immense efforts. Now without further adieu, I invite you to the deadliest course in Chessable History. Let’s Roar with  1.e4  . }
