1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Sicilian Nimzowitsch Variation.It bears some similarity to Alekhine's Defence by trying to provoke us to play e5 and then undermine it. The question here is that of course if he is able to undermine it effectively or not, otherwise it simply gives White more space. This move is rarely seen at the elite level but once in a while, even strong players employ it as a surprise weapon and quite a popular move in rapid/blitz games. }
3. e5
{ Of course! Given a chance, we roar :@@EndBracket@@ After all we are wolves! }
3... Nd5 4. Nc3 { Challenging the Knight on d5 which is quite active. } 4... e6
{ Holding the Knight on d5 tight, for the moment. } 5. Ne4
{ 5.Nxd5  is the mainline but leads to some crazy stuff after  5...exd5  6.d4  Nc6  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.Qxd5  Qb6  9.Bc4  Bxf2  10.Ke2  . Do we need all these complications when we have a simple solution in hand? I don't think so, hence 5.Ne4! }
5... Nc6 { This move is too weak, too slow and we can pester the d5 Knight. }
6. c4 { Hunting down the d5 Knight. } 6... f5
{ Leads to some forced consequences. } 7. cxd5 fxe4 8. dxc6 exf3
{ And suddenly all the Knights on the board have disappeared :@@EndBracket@@ }
9. Qxf3
{ 9.cxd7  wins a pawn but it helps Black develop his c8 Bishop. So instead of winning a pawn, our main goal is to restrict the c8 Bishop. }
9... dxc6
{ And now look at the poor Bishop on c8. On top of that Black's pawn structure is damaged. }
10. Be2 Qd4 11. Qc3 { With easy play for White. } *

