1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6
{ The O'Kelly Variation.Black's idea is to meet  3.d4  with  3...cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  e5  when 6.Ndb5 is prevented thanks to the pawn on a6, and after  6.Nb3  or  6.Nf3  Black will equalize by playing  6...Bb4  followed by striking in the centre with ...d5.   However, White may avoid this by instead playing  3.c3  or  3.c4  .  The Chuck Norris of Russian team, Mr. Artemiev has played O'Kelly system heavily in his recent online games. When I switch on my online database, I could find more or less 20-30 games of him :@@EndBracket@@ O'Kelly turning into the Chuck Norris variation :@@EndBracket@@ Perhaps who knows :@@EndBracket@@    To know why Artemiev is called the Chuck Norris, you guys will have to watch the press conference of Grischuk after the Russian Team won the World teams 2019. It's right available on Youtube. And yes on the way you can also find these Thug Life compilations of Sasha :@@EndBracket@@ It's damn hilarious :@@EndBracket@@Enough of stories, let's get back to the variation :@@EndBracket@@ }
3. c3
{ We are aiming for d4 now, in the style of Alapin. We clearly have a better version of the Alapin as our Knight is on f3 whereas Black has a pawn on the rim of the board that is a6. }
3... Nf6
{ This is one option, attacking the e4 pawn, but we advance our pawn. } 4. e5
{ The standard response, harassing the Knight. } 4... Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. Bc4
{ And this is a significant intermezzo pestering the Knight on d5 and wielding pressure on the c4-f7 diagonal. }
6... Nb6
{ 6...e6  is met with  7.Bxd5  exd5  8.Qxd4  and the d5 pawn falls apart. So Black cannot hold the d5 Knight there anymore. }
7. Bb3 { The pressure on the b3-f7 diagonal is powerful. } 7... dxc3
