1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ Yes, I am not going to deviate with  3.Bb5  and all kinds of Rossolimo. I am ready to dive into the sea of the open positions and hence staying true to the pack, that is The Wolf Pack, we steer into open positions by blowing up the centre. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 { The starting position. } 5... e5
{ The Sveshnikov Variation was pioneered by Evgeny Sveshnikov and Gennadi Timoshchenko in the 1970s. Before their efforts, the variation was called the Lasker–Pelikan Variation. Emanuel Lasker played it once in his world championship match against Carl Schlechter, and Jorge Pelikan played it a few times in the 1950s, but Sveshnikov's treatment of the variation was the key to its revitalization.The move 5...e5 seems anti-positional as it leaves Black with a backward d pawn and a weakness on d5. Also, Black has to accept doubled f-pawns in the mainline of the opening. However, in return, Black gets a foothold in the centre and gains time on White's knight, which has been driven to the edge of the board on a3.Today, this variation is extremely popular among grandmasters and amateurs alike. Top players who have used this variation include Magnus Carlsen, Vladimir Kramnik, Veselin Topalov, Teimour Radjabov, Boris Gelfand, Michael Adams and Alexander Khalifman, among many others.And the Sveshnikov Variation became even more popular after Magnus Carlsen employed it in his World Championship Match against Caruana. }
6. Ndb5 { The theoretically critical move, threatening Nd6+. } 6... d6
{ The main continuation, preventing the Nd6 invasion. Next Black will play ...a6 and kick the Knight to the rim of the board. }
7. Nd5
{ 7.Bg5  is the old mainline with tons of games and complicated theoretical battles.Recently this idea of 7.Nd5 became insanely popular thanks to Vladimir Kramnik, who was one of the few elite players to initiate this tabiya in modern times. He is indeed the trend setter when it comes to opening ideas. }
7... Nxd5 { Forced, otherwise White was going to play Nc7+. } 8. exd5
{ And here there are two main Knight retreats  8...Ne7  and  8...Nb8  .  The former is more concrete and leads to a narrow path where several only moves are required from Black to survive White's initiative. And the latter, with 8... Nb8, is more logical to develop the Knight to d7 in the future and is more solid. }
8... Ne7
{ Black with this option wants to get the Knight immediately to the Kingside, either to f5 or g6. }
9. c4
{ The critical move, strengthening the pawn on d5 and paving way for the Queen on d1 to a4 to create a stir before Black consolidates. }
9... Ng6
{ Black's intention is to play Be7, castle and follow up with the pawn roll with ...f5. The direct  9...a6  fails to the standard  10.Qa4  and Black cannot interpose with  10...Bd7  due to  11.Nxd6  mate. }
10. Qa4
{ With discovery threats floating in the air. Also, White's main idea to maneuver the Queen to a3 or b4 to target the d6 pawn is on the cards. }
10... Bd7 { The only move, blocking the a4-e8 diagonal. } 11. Qb4
{ Exerting pressure on the d6 pawn. } 11... Bf5 12. h4
{ Threatening h5 to corner the Knight on g6. Black has various ways of reacting and they will be analyzed in turn in the corresponding set of trainables in the Sveshnikov chapter. }
