{ Yes, I am not going to deviate with  3.Bb5  and all kinds of Rossolimo. I am ready to dive into the sea of the open positions and hence staying true to the pack, that is The Wolf Pack, we steer into open positions by blowing up the centre. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ The Accelerated Dragon! Like the Standard Dragon Variation, Black develops the Bishop to g7 in the Accelerated Dragon. But the major difference here is that Black avoids playing ...d7–d6 and can later play ...d7–d5 in one move if possible.   For example, if White tries to play in the style of the Yugoslav Attack with  5.Nc3  Bg7  6.Be3  Nf6  7.f3  O-O  8.Qd2  ,  then  8...d5!  equalizes immediately. So unlike in the normal Dragon, Black delays playing the move ...d6 for as long as possible, prioritizing piece development instead.   The critical test of Black's move order is  5.c4  ,  the Maróczy Bind. White hopes to cramp Black's position by impeding the ...d7–d5 and ...b7–b5 pawn thrusts. Generally, this line is less tactical than many of the other Sicilian variations, and play involves much strategic maneuvering on both sides. }
5. c4
{ The Maroczy Bind! Gaining space immediately. And by the way, I read a very nice book by Andrian Mikhalchishin and Georg Mohr on Understanding Maroczy structures by Thinkers Publishing. It deals with the Maroczy structure arising from various different openings. A beautiful book, I must say, illustrating the typical plans and motifs.So let's go ahead now with the opening phase. }
5... Bg7 6. Be3 { Strengthening the Knight on d4. } 6... Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be2
{ Lucid play from White. } 8... d6 9. O-O Bd7
{ Maintaining the tension on d4. However, next Black is going to take the Knight on d4 and follow it with ...Bc6. }
10. h3
{ Of course, there is one more interesting option of  10.Nc2  maintaining more pieces. }
10... Nxd4
{ If  10...Rc8  then we have  11.Re1  Nxd4  12.Bxd4  Bc6  and here comes  13.b4  due to the point that the e4 pawn cannot be taken, thanks to a nice tactic after  13...Nxe4  14.Bxg7  Kxg7  15.Nxe4  Bxe4  16.Qd4+  and White wins. }
11. Bxd4 Bc6
{ The main plan for Black in these structures is to exchange as many pieces as possible and free his position. This is one of the golden rules when you lack space. }
12. Qc2
{ We can as well play  12.Qd3  ,  but we are not in time to expand with b4 as after  12...a5  13.b3  Nd7  14.Bxg7  Kxg7  15.a3  Black gets  15...Nc5  in time, followed by ...e5 and ...Ne6 securing a nice position for his Knight on the d4 square. Once he achieves it, then he is more or less fine. So we have to shift our plans to 12. Qc2. }
12... a5
{ Preventing the b4 expansion is quite logical. If  12...Nd7  then  13.Bxg7  Kxg7  14.b4  we get our ideal setup. }
13. b3 { a3-b4 is the typical plan here. } 13... Nd7 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Rfd1
{ And this is the key nuance in order to meet  15...Nc5  with  16.e5  .  That is the reason we place the Queen on c2, to keep the d-file open for the Rook. You can find a more detailed analysis of this position in the corresponding chapter. }
