{ I was struggling with my choice against the Najdorf and it took the most of my time to come up with a direction. I was mainly hesitating between 6. Be3 the English attack and 6. Bg5, and finally decided to dive deep into the ocean of crazy razor sharp positions after 6. Bg5. Yes, we enter into the world of topsy-turvy battles. This is the most principled mainline, which always has a dangerous reputation and indeed it still holds to the test of being deadly as you can witness the recent duel between Caruana-Vachier in Candidates 2020-2021 where it proved its worth.   I have seen many Najdorf players being afraid to face this move but the only point is that it involves a lot of theory and long lines. But at some point, if you want to be a good chess player, you have to employ principled main lines and of course, when you play principled lines it is bound to happen that you have to enter long lines. The point of the move 6. Bg5 is obviously to keep pressure on the f6 Knight and follow up with f4-Qf3 and long castle. }
6... e6
