1. e4 c6
{ The Caro–Kann Defence!! This opening is named after the English player, Horatio Caro and the Austrian player, Marcus Kann, who analysed it in 1886. :@@EndBracket@@    Black plans to challenge the centre with ...d5 next. The Caro-Kann became extremely popular thanks to the efforts of World Champion Anatoly Karpov who played it regularly and successfully. Recently there are many books and courses on the Caro-Kann @@StartBracket@@for instance the famous Chessable course of Erwin L'Ami contributes largely to the opening.@@EndBracket@@ It is a solid opening with lots of flexible plans and layers to it. }
2. d4
{ Towards the centre as always. :@@EndBracket@@ This is the principled choice. }
2... d5 3. e5
{ Apart from  3.Nc3  ,  the Advance Variation with 3. e5 tends to be the acid test for Black players in modern days. White simply gains space by this advance.   The Advance Variation with  3.e5  has gained popularity after having previously been widely regarded as inferior for many years, owing chiefly to the strategic demolition that Aron Nimzowitsch @@StartBracket@@playing as White@@EndBracket@@ suffered at the hands of José Capablanca in one of their games at the New York 1927 tournament.  The Advance Variation has since been revitalized by aggressive lines such as the Bayonet Attack @@StartBracket@@  3.e5  Bf5  4.Nc3  e6  5.g4  @@EndBracket@@  a popular line in the 1980s and later favoured by Latvian grandmaster Alexei Shirov.   There is also the recent trendy ambitious variation with  3.e5  Bf5  4.Nf3  e6  5.Be2  c5  6.Be3  popularised by English grandmaster Nigel Short and often seen in the 1990s.   Another aggressive line is the Tal variation @@StartBracket@@  3.e5  Bf5  4.h4  h5  @@EndBracket@@  popularised by grandmaster Mikhail Tal. This is what we are going to deal with in this Chapter. }
3... c5
{ The  3...c5  variation is an important alternative and avoids the weight of theory associated with  3...Bf5  . It was used by Mikhail Botvinnik in his 1961 match versus Mikhail Tal @@StartBracket@@though with a negative outcome for Botvinnik – two draws and a loss@@EndBracket@@. The line was christened the 'Arkell/ Khenkin Variation' in the leading chess magazine, New in Chess Yearbook 42 in recognition of the work these two grandmasters did and the success they were having with the variation.   In comparison to the French Defence, Black lacks the tempo normally spent on ...e6, but nevertheless Black goes ahead to challenge White's central pawn on d4. In recent years this option has gained immense popularity among the top players. }
4. Nf3
{ Of course, grabbing the pawn on c5 with  4.dxc5  is more principled but leads to complex play with crazy computer stuffed analysis as witnessed in Wesley So's Chessable course. To the contrary, 4. Nf3 is more simple. White develops the Knight and this leads to pleasant positions for White avoiding the heaps of theory after 4. dxc5. }
4... Bg4
{ Pinning the Knight on f3. This was played in olden days by strong Grandmasters but later lost its charm due to the fact that White found new directions to secure an advantage here. }
5. dxc5
{ Now it's time to grab the pawn on c5 as the position of the pieces have drastically changed from the last two moves. }
5... e6
{ 5...Nc6  is the mainline and it transposes to the 4...Nc6 5.dxc5 Bg4 line. }
6. Bb5+ Nd7
{ 6...Nc6  will be met by  7.b4  holding the pawn on c5  7...a5  8.c3  and Black is a pawn down with not enough compensation. }
7. b4
{ Given a chance, of course we have to give support to the key pawn on c5. }
7... a5 { Trying to break the pawn chain but we can strengthen it. } 8. c3 Ne7
{ With the idea of ...Nc6 targetting the pawn on e5. } 9. Nbd2 Nc6 10. Qe2
{ Holding the pawn on c5. White is slightly better thanks to the extra pawn. }
