1. e4 e6
{ The FRENCH!! The idea behind the French Defense is that Black plays e6 to prepare to advance d7-d5, in order to immediately challenge White’s pawn on e4. But the biggest problem is that the c8 Bishop is blocked by the very first move of 1...e6 and often minimizes its scope. Many times the entire game will revolve around this fundamental weakness. }
2. d4
{ A logical move towards the centre. There are some funky or offbeat lines like  2.Qe2  stopping ...d5 but then Black can play  2...c5  transposing to a Sicilian where our Queen is not ideally placed on e2. Nevertheless this has been tried and tested in many top-level games as it avoids heaps of theoretical debates. But let's stick to the principled option here. :@@EndBracket@@ }
2... d5 3. Nc3
{ Placing the Knight on a more active square which supports the e4 pawn, maintaining the tension.   Apart from that,  3.e5  and  3.Nd2  are the other main options.   3.Nd2  is  equally popular, advocated by Wesley So in his Chessable courses, but my main concern was that the Knight on d2 blocks the c1 Bishop. Likewise  3.e5  clarifies tension in the centre in a quick manner. So if we look from a principled point of view brutally then 3. Nc3 is in the spirit of the position and is the option that Black players are really afraid to face while employing the French. :@@EndBracket@@ }
3... dxe4
{ The Rubinstein Variation!! This variation is named after Akiba Rubinstein and can also arise from a different move order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3.Nd2  dxe4  White has free development and more space in the centre which Black intends to neutralise by playing ...c7–c5 at some point.   This solid line has undergone a modest revival, featuring in many GM games as a drawing weapon but theory still gives White a slight edge. The plus point of White is the c3 Knight gets activated, thanks to this exchange and he also maximizes the scope of his Knight on e4. }
4. Nxe4 Nf6
{ Black challenges our Knight on e4 immediately but the major drawback is that he has to recapture with the Queen or the pawn upon  5.Nxf6+  and both of these recaptures are not ideal.  5...Qxf6  would venture the Queen into the game too quickly and can be harassed.   Taking with pawn with  5...gxf6  will of course weaken the King's position and will lead to doubled pawns. Let's check both these options in-depth. }
5. Nxf6+ gxf6
{ Employed by the creative Hungarian superstar Richard Rapport but of course, objectively this is not a good sign for Black to double his pawns and weaken his King too early in the game. }
6. Nf3 b6 7. Bb5+
{ This annoying check disrupts Black's harmony as  7...c6  would block his c8 Bishop totally. }
7... c6
{ What else to do?  7...Bd7  would not make much sense as the point of ...b6 was to place the Bishop on b7.  8.Bd3  and if  8...Bc6  here trying to retain the diagonal then  9.O-O  Nd7  10.Re1  followed by c4-d5 and the Bishop is clearly misplaced on c6. }
8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Bf4 c5 10. Qe2
{ Followed by long castle and Black is in trouble with his King in the centre unable to castle on either side. }
