1. e4 e6
{ The FRENCH!! The idea behind the French Defense is that Black plays e6 to prepare to advance d7-d5, in order to immediately challenge White’s pawn on e4. But the biggest problem is that the c8 Bishop is blocked by the very first move of 1...e6 and often minimizes its scope. Many times the entire game will revolve around this fundamental weakness. }
2. d4
{ A logical move towards the centre. There are some funky or offbeat lines like  2.Qe2  stopping ...d5 but then Black can play  2...c5  transposing to a Sicilian where our Queen is not ideally placed on e2. Nevertheless this has been tried and tested in many top-level games as it avoids heaps of theoretical debates. But let's stick to the principled option here. :@@EndBracket@@ }
2... d5 3. Nc3
{ Placing the Knight on a more active square which supports the e4 pawn, maintaining the tension.   Apart from that,  3.e5  and  3.Nd2  are the other main options.   3.Nd2  is  equally popular, advocated by Wesley So in his Chessable courses, but my main concern was that the Knight on d2 blocks the c1 Bishop. Likewise  3.e5  clarifies tension in the centre in a quick manner. So if we look from a principled point of view brutally then 3. Nc3 is in the spirit of the position and is the option that Black players are really afraid to face while employing the French. :@@EndBracket@@ }
3... Bb4
{ This is called the Winawer Variation, named after Szymon Winawer and pioneered by Nimzowitsch and Botvinnik. It is one of the main systems in the French apart from  3...N  f6  .   The point of  3...Bb4  is that it pins the knight on c3, forcing White to resolve the central tension. White normally clarifies the central situation for the moment with  4.e5  ,  gaining space and hoping to show that Black's b4-bishop is misplaced. P.S Anish in his French defense course has recommended the move 3... Bb4. }
4. e5
{ There are some funkier tries for White: to hold the pawn on e4 by  4.Bd3  , aggressive ones like  4.Nge2  , and quieter ones like  4.exd5  , but  4.e5  is the main principled line advancing further and gaining space. }
4... c5 { Challenging the centre immediately without any delay. } 5. a3
{ The mainline - asking questions to the Bishop on b4. } 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3
{ White has doubled pawns on the Queenside, which form the basis for Black's counterplay. They can also help White since they strengthen his centre and give him a semi-open b-file. White has a spatial advantage on the Kingside, where Black is even weaker than usual because he has traded off his dark-squared Bishop. Combined with the Bishop pair, this gives White attacking chances, which he must attempt to use as the long-term features of this pawn structure favour Black. }
6... Ne7 7. Qg4 Qc7 { Creating counterplay against the c3 pawn. } 8. Bd3
{ A totally new system which gained immense popurality after Parimarjan Negi devised this interesting direction in his book Grandmaster Repotire for Quality chess. The mainline remains the crazy  8.Qxg7  Rg8  9.Qxh7  cxd4  and this razor sharp line is played very often, with tons of games and theoretical debates. }
8... c4
{ This obvious move is dubious as it releases the tension and White has a free ride on the kingside afterward. }
9. Be2 Qa5
{ This was the main recommendation of Anish Giri in his Chessable course. The Queen on a5 pressures the pawn on c3, but I don't like these positions for Black generally as he has released his tension with ...c4. It is now a question whether White can break open and create a point of entry or not.   Black has to sit and watch while White can execute his plans, although White has to choose his plans carefully in order to break the wall. It's a complex strategical struggle, but White should be on top. Let us see some schematic ideas and plans as there are fewer games here than in some other variations. }
10. Bd2 { Supporting the pawn on c3. } 10... Rg8
{ This was also one of the moves suggested by Anish in his course apart from  10...Nf5  . }
11. a4
{ The best move as we prevent...Qa4 and create more space for our pieces. }
11... Bd7 12. Qf4
{ With the idea of Bh5 sometimes and to exert pressure on the f7 pawn. The Queen on f4 keeps an eye on the f7 pawn, which makes it hard for Black to castle long after ...Bd7. }
12... Bxa4 { Black grabs the pawn but his Bishop gets locked now. } 13. Bh5
{ Apart from the  13.h4  idea, which will be examined later in the final Winawer chapter as an alternative, this plan - which we have never witnessed before - is very interesting and perhaps the strongest according to both the virtual monsters Leela Zero and Stockfish. This is a rare sight as in most of the positions these engines contradict each other. }
13... Rf8
{ 13...Ng6  will lose the flexibility of the Knight as it can no longer hop to f5.  14.Qg3  Qb5  15.Bd1  followed by Qh3-f4-g4-Ne2. }
14. Qg3 Nf5 15. Qh3
{ 15...Qb5  Untangling his pieces, is also possible. But this is met with  16.Bd1  followed by f4 and g4 and Black is in big trouble. }
15... Ne7 16. Ne2
{ Followed by Nf4, O-O, removing the Bishop from h5 and then advancing our pawns with g4, Nh5, f4 and all that jazz. }
