{ And the Rook on h8 is hanging. Black is suffering on the dark squares and it is not time to land the Dragon Bishop. }
5... Nf6 6. b4 { White plans for some concrete action with his pawn thrust. }
6... Qd8 7. e5
{ Time is precious. We don't waste any and go for annihilation. } 7... Nc6
{ Black has to disturb our Queen first before moving the Knight from  f6  . For instance, if  7...Nh5  we can simply play  8.b5  and seal the Knight on  c6  and the Queen will dominate on  d4  and if  8...Bg7  then  9.g4  traps the Knight on the rim of the board. }
8. Qh4 Nh5 9. Bb2
{ One of the advantages of having our pawn on b4 is that we get the b2 square for the Bishop. And can we call the b2 Bishop 'The Beastly Bishop' :@@EndBracket@@ Rofl. You might wonder why, here goes the reason, my good friend Adhiban is fond of 1.b3-Bb2 as the whole world knows by now, thanks to his amazing tagging skills in Twitter, and in fact, he sabotaged the name of Nimzo Larsen and framed a new term calling b3 as Beast Attack. So obviously the bishop who goes to b2 should also be called the Beast Bishop. }
9... Bg7 10. Nd5
{ Sneaking in and Black is in big trouble as g4 is coming next. } *

