1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ To some, this is called the Paulsen variation, after the 19th-century master Louis Paulsen. To others, it is the Kan variation, named after the Soviet theoretician Ilya Kan. By playing 4...a6, Black prevents Nb5 and prepares an eventual ...b5 advance followed by...Bb7. On the other hand, Black only wastes some time in moving his pawns rather than his pieces and as well the move...a6 is not focused towards the centre. So in this regard, it gives free play for White with many flexible options to gain space and be ambitious. }
5. Bd3
{ 5.c4  and  5.Nc3  are the other two options here. With the text move 5. Bd3 White overprotects the pawn on e4 and aims for a quick castle. Black has a hell of a lot of options here. }
5... Bc5
{ Making use of the fact that the d3 Bishop is hindering the Queen on d1 to support the d4 Knight but White can retract his Knight with tempo with }
6. Nb3 { And Black has two ways to retreat either to a7 or to e7. } 6... Ba7
{ Maintaining the diagonal. } 7. Qe2
{ So that we can challenge the a7 Bishop by Be3 next. } 7... Nc6 8. Be3 Nge7
{ 8...d6  will transpose to 7...d6 line. } 9. Nc3
{ With the intention of long castling of course. } 9... b5
{ Trying to create some play but here we shift our plans. } 10. Bxa7 Rxa7 11.
a4
{ 11.O-O-O  is also definitely possible but perhaps this break is even stronger. }
11... b4 12. Nd5
{ We have this nice resource, otherwise there was no point with the a4 break.   12.Nd1  was played in the game of Anand-Kamsky but the text is obviously way stronger. }
12... O-O
{ 12...exd5  13.exd5  and Black cannot save one of the Knights as dxc6 and d6 is a multiple threat and White regains the piece with a great advantage. }
13. Nxe7+ Qxe7 14. Qe3 { Keeping an eye on the a7 Rook. } 14... d6 15. f4 Bd7
16. O-O-O
{ And once again White maintains a nice advantage thanks to more space and commanding pieces. The Queen on e3 can enter into b6 next and Black is falling apart or as well we can play Qd2, Bc4 and attack the weak pawn on d6. }
