{ The Caro–Kann Defence!! This opening is named after the English player Horatio Caro and the Austrian player Marcus Kann, who analysed it in 1886. :@@EndBracket@@    Black plans to challenge the centre with ...d5 next. Caro-Kann became extremely popular thanks to the efforts of World Champion Anatoly Karpov who played it it regularly and successfully. Recently there are many books and courses on Caro-Kann @@StartBracket@@for instance the famous Chessable course of Erwin L'Ami contributes largely to the opening.@@EndBracket@@ It is a solid opening with lots of flexible plans and layers to it. }
2. d4
{ Towards the centre as always :@@EndBracket@@ is the principled choice. } 2...
d5 3. e5
{ Apart from  3.Nc3  ,  the Advance Variation with 3. e5 tends to be the acid test for Black players in modern days. White simply gains space by this advance.   The Advance Variation with 3. e5 has gained popularity after having previously been widely regarded as inferior for many years, owing chiefly to the strategic demolition that Aron Nimzowitsch @@StartBracket@@playing as White@@EndBracket@@ suffered at the hands of José Capablanca in one of their games at the New York 1927 tournament.   The Advance Variation has since been revitalized by aggressive lines such as the Bayonet Attack  @@StartBracket@@  3.e5  Bf5  4.Nc3  e6  5.g4  @@EndBracket@@  a popular line in the 1980s and later favoured by Latvian grandmaster Alexei Shirov.   There is also the recent trendy ambitious variation with  3.e5  Bf5  4.Nf3  e6  5.Be2  c5  6.Be3  popularised by English grandmaster Nigel Short which was often seen in the 1990s.   Another less popular but aggressive line is the Tal variation @@StartBracket@@  3.e5  Bf5  4.h4  h5  @@EndBracket@@  popularised by grandmaster Mikhail Tal. This is what we are going to deal with in this Chapter. }
3... Bf5
{ By far the most popular response to the Advance Varation, and a very logical one as Black gets to develop the Bishop before playing e7-e6. That is the difference between the French and Caro Kann. In the French, the c8 Bishop is locked from move one which is not the case with the Caro Kann. }
4. h4
{ The Tal Variation. In the spirit of the Magician, Mikhail Tal. This move Grabs space on the Kingside and White is planning to roll with g4 next and Black can no longer maintain the Bishop on the f5-h7 diagonal as ...Bg6 will lead to h5 trapping the Bishop. That is the main point of advancing with h4 first so that White can harass the f5 bishop and as well expand more space which will be useful in the future to create an attack.   And yeah it avoids Black's intended  4...e6  as it fails miserably to  5.g4  Be4  6.f3  Bg6  7.h5  trapping the Bishop. }
4... h5
{ The mainline, fixing the pawns on the h-file and preventing White's further expansion with g4 and all that stuff. }
5. Bd3
{ Exchanging the active Bishop on f5 as after ...h5 he is well secured. } 5...
Bxd3 6. Qxd3
{ The critical juncture. Black has two ideas here: either to venture with the Queen out by  6...Qa5+  ,  which is the mainline, with the idea of exchanging the Queens with 7...Qa6 next,  or  6...e6  simply developing the pieces. }
6... e6 7. Bg5
{ One of the advantages of having the pawn on h4. White disturbs the Black Queen. }
7... Qb6
{ Keeping an eye on the b2 pawn and preparing ...c5 break next. This tabiya leads to concrete complex lines. So let's go ahead. }
8. Nd2 Nd7 { is also slow. } 9. Ngf3 Ne7 10. O-O Nf5 11. c4
{ The important breakthrough from White's side which creates a lot of problems for Black in the centre and also prevents him from breaking with ...c5. }
11... Qa6
{ Happened in the online game of Nakamura-Carlsen 2020 but Black's position is bad... }
12. Qc3
{ Drifting away from the a6-d3 diagonal and also preventing ...Bb4 stuff from Black. }
12... dxc4 13. Nxc4 Nb6
{ This was the idea behind releasing the tension so that Black can occupy the d5 square but he is still not in time... }
14. Ne3 Ne7
{ With the intention to grab the d5 square but like I said he has wasted so many moves for that and will make no effect even if he occupies it. }
15. Qc2 Ned5 16. Rfd1 Be7 17. Bxe7 Nxe7 18. Rd3
{ And the Rook is landing on a3 harassing the Queen on a6. Black is clearly worse here. }
