{ Placing the Knight in a more active square which supports the e4 pawn, maintaining the tension. Apart from that,   3.e5  and 3. Nd2 are the other main options.   3.Nd2  is also equally popular, advocated by Wesley So in his Opening series, but my main concern was that the Knight on d2 blocks the c1 Bishop, likewise 3. e5 clarifies tension in the centre in a quick manner. So if we look from a principled point of view brutally then 3. Nc3 is in the spirit of the position and is the one where Black players are really afraid to face while employing the French. :@@EndBracket@@ }
