{ The battle of the two best specialists of the Sveshnikov Variation at that time was of great interest, and even today it is. :@@EndBracket@@ So let's check their game which corresponds with our opening suggestion. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5
{ At that time, this direction was not that famous. People religiously used to play the mainline with   7.Bg5  a6  8.Na3  b5  and all those forcing lines. As the theory exploded, White had to come back and seek a new direction and that's how the new trend of 7. Nd5 was revived once again. So in this old game, this was relatively new. }
7... Nxd5 8. exd5 Nb8
{ This retreat is the main move here. The knight comes to d7, where he can choose later which direction to go: c5, e5, or f6.   Apart from 8...Nb8 there is also  8...Ne7  which is dealt with extensively in the opening section. This whole tabiya became extremely popular after the World Championship match between Carlsen and Caruana. }
9. c4 { Buidling up a formidable centre. } 9... Be7 10. Bd3 a6 11. Nc3 O-O 12.
O-O f5
{ Logical moves from both sides. For deviations and other Black options, you can always head to the opening section. Our main criteria is to learn the typical ideas and plans from the game, so let's quickly hop to the critical juncture where the opening sort of ends. }
13. f3 Bg5 14. Kh1
{ 14.Qc2  is the critical move suggested by me in the opening section creating pressure along the c2-h7 diagonal. It is more effective but the move played in the game is also natural. }
14... Nd7 15. b4
{ Both sides make 'their' moves. White traditionally seizes space on the Queenside, while Black is trying to create something in center and on the Kingside. But one point to add is that 15. b4 is imprecise here and 15. a3 has to be played, preparing the b4 push with the same notion.   So why 15.  a3  and not  15.b4?  The simple point is that Black now gets to break with  15...a5  .   After  15.a3  he has to wait for one more move as  15...a5  without us playing b4 weakens the b5 square, without any counterplay in return. So after 15. a3 we get formidable support for our b4 pawn when we push it on the next move. }
15... a5 16. a3 axb4
{ 16...e4  here is a brilliant resource and typical pawn sacrifice for Black which we have to be aware of always as after  17.fxe4  Black has a strong maneuver with  17...Bf6  18.Bd2  Be5  and the Queen is arriving to h4 with great counterplay. }
17. Bxg5 Qxg5 18. axb4 Rxa1 19. Qxa1
{ Now the position has fizzled out. That's is also one of the reasons why we should play 16. a3 and then b4, maintaining the flexibility. }
19... Qe3 20. Be2
{ Prepares 21. Qc1 next, using the fact that endgame favours White and as well the Queen is quite annoying on e3. }
20... e4
{ Krasenkow is not willing to play a passive position and is looking for immediate activity and his move 20...e4 showcases it. One of Black's typical breaks but only in this position it is not that effective as White gets Qc1 in time and Black will have to either exchange it which loses all his ambition or retract back which will slow his activity.   Instead  20...Nf6  was required:  21.Qc1  Qb6  22.Nb5  Bd7  23.c5  Qa6  and apparently Black is holding this complex game. }
21. Qc1 Qb6
{ Exchanging the Queens will only help White to a greater extent:  21...Qxc1  22.Rxc1  exf3  23.gxf3!  quite important and next White is pouncing with Nb5 and c5. }
22. fxe4
{ 23.Nb5  was necessary as the b4 pawn was hanging and White is the boss there. }
22... fxe4
{ 22...Qxb4  would have equalised easily:  23.exf5  Ne5  and Black is back in the game. }
23. Rxf8+ Nxf8 24. Nb5
{ Now Black is again in a doomed situation as his e4 pawn stands lonely. Also, c5 is a dangerous threat now. }
24... Ng6 { 24...Qf2  is faced by  25.Qf1  . } 25. c5 dxc5 26. bxc5
{ Extremely natural, but the computers don't agree. They prefer 26. Qxc5 with a huge advantage whereas 26. bxc5 simply loses all our advantage. This is such a drastic difference, but I can understand now why is that as 26. Qxc5 simply kills the active piece of Black whereas in the other case it does not.   So  26.Qxc5  Qd8  27.d6  is winning for White. }
26... Qf6
{ And once again Black is back in the game with the Knight heading to f4. } 27.
Nd6 Nf4 { Finally, Black has some activity. } 28. Nxe4
{ 28.Bc4  might be more challenging but after the only brilliant move  28...Nd3  which is tough to spot, Black is fine in the ensuing complications.  29.Bxd3  exd3  30.Nxc8  is a blunder and would allow d2 and Qf2 and Black is winning.   So after  28...Nd3  White has to play  29.Qb1  with a complex game. }
28... Qe5 29. Bf3 Nxd5
{ Black has equalised completely but he still has some things to solve before shaking hands. }
30. Nd6 Be6 31. Nxb7 Nf4 32. c6
{ The position is heating up and Black has to find only concrete moves to save the position from drowning. }
32... Nd3 33. Qf1 Ne1 { Sealing White's pieces. } 34. Be2 Nc2
{ Missing the chance to force matters:  34...Nxg2!!  would most likely have given him a draw. But it's not an easy move to spot. The line continues with  35.Kxg2  Bd5+  36  Bf3  Qg5  37.Kf2  Bxf3  38.Kxf3  Qf5+  39.Ke2  Qe5  40.Kd2  Qb2  and Black achieves a perpetual. But the text move is possible and Black is still not losing. }
35. Bc4 Ne3
{ Now comes the big blunder.  35...Bxc4  would have kept drawing chances alive after  36.Qxc4  Kh8  37.Qc5  Qa1+  38.Qg1  Qe5  and it not easy for White to advance his c pawn. }
36. Bxe6+ Qxe6 37. Qf4
{ The only winning move, with the point that  37...Qxc6  38.Qb8  Kf7  39.Nd8  is game over. }
37... h6 38. Nc5 Qe8 39. Nd3
{ Covering the e1 square as the last trap was  39.c7  Nd5  and 40... Nxc7. }
39... Kh7 40. c7 Qe6 41. Qe5
{ And White won the game. So many interesting ideas and plans to learn from this game. }
