{ Now we will see one of my own games from the French 3. Nc3 Nf6 lines. My win against Grandmaster Akobian was so special for me that I can easily regard it as one of my best games in terms of quality. And as well considering the tournament situation it was such a relief to continue the winning streak from a 0/3 horrible start in the Saint Louis Closed Event. Later I went on to win four games in a row and this win came in mid-way. So I was extremely glad not only to win this game, but also to play a positional masterpiece in the French. I have showcased this game in various chess lectures and thought it would be a nice addition here as well. So let's proceed. }
1. e4 e6
{ Akobian is an ardent French player, but in the previous event of the Fall Chess Classic in Saint Louis, he opted for the Scandinavian which is in fact analysed in my Part 1 of my 1. e4 series. :@@EndBracket@@ but after getting crushed in the previous tournament game, I can understand that this time Akobian wanted to stick to his main arsenal. }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ Lately, I have always responded with 3. Nc3 against the French and it has been my main weapon because I believe it to be the one direction that poses problems for Black theoretically. }
3... Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 { White builds up ample space. } 6... Nc6
7. Be3 a6
{ This is one of the lines apart from  7...Be7  and  7...b6  and so many others which we have dealt with in the openings section. This includes chapters 17-19 of the course. The point of 7...a6 is of course to induce ...b5. }
8. a3
{ 8.Qd2  b5  is regarded as the old mainline.   The text move with  8.a3  is the new trend and contains many interesting ideas. The point of this move  8.a3  is very subtle, namely to meet  8...b5  with  9.dxc5  and after massive exchanges on c5 White will sabotage Black's Queenside totally by playing b4. This is the key point behind a3 pawn push. }
8... cxd4
{ 8...b5  9.dxc5  Bxc5  10.Bxc5  Nxc5  and  11.b4  is the sneaky plan and Black's Queenside is sealed.  11...Nd7  12.Bd3  and White has a comfortable advantage. }
9. Nxd4 Bc5
{ On the previous move Black clarified matters in the centre in order to bring this f8 Bishop into the game. And now this bishop quite active on c5, putting pressure on the d4 Knight. }
10. Qd2 { Long castling is one of the ideas here. } 10... O-O
{ Actually, I had two games here in this particular position. The first one was against a strong Armenian Woman Grandmaster Danielian and the second one is the game we are looking at. Apparently my opponent had checked that game but I had an improvement up my sleeves. :@@EndBracket@@ }
11. h4
{ This is the key nuance and the correct move order.   In my first game against Danielian, I played  11.O-O-O  instantly without understanding the difference between first 11. h4 before long castling.   If  11.O-O-O  then Black has this option of  11...Bxd4  12.Bxd4  b5  followed by Rb8 with decent counterplay against White's King. We get more or less similar positions in the 11. h4 line too, but there our pawn will already be advanced to h5 which is definitely a better version for White. :@@EndBracket@@ So in a way, we are not hurrying up with long castle and improving our position with the battering h pawn. }
11... Nxd4
{ 11...Bxd4  12.Bxd4  b5  is not effective here as we have not castled long, and we simply retreat our Bishop to f2 by  13.Bf2  maintaining the Bishop pair. In fact, we can shift our plan to castling short. :@@EndBracket@@ That's is why 11. h4 is more flexible. }
12. Bxd4 b5 { Akobian has played natural moves so far. } 13. O-O-O Rb8
{ Once again, it looks logical to prepare ...b4 as the direct  13...b4  fails to  14.Bxc5  bxc3  15.Qxc3  . }
14. Bxc5
{ Now it's time to release the tension in order to stop Black's only counterplay with the ...b4 break. }
14... Nxc5 15. Qd4
{ Centralizing the Queen and preventing ...b4. In the openings section, I have recommended an even stronger move with  15.b4!!  which is a positional masterpiece sabotaging Black's play completely.  15...Nd7  16.Ne2  & Nd4 and White is dominating. The move played in the game is also quite good leading to a similar situation. }
15... Qc7
{ Holding the Knight on c5. We cannot pinpoint a single mistake from Black as he has played all logical moves but Black's position is already falling apart. That showcases that the direction of this line is not in the right spirit. As always the c8 Bishop gets stuck like in many French positions and we make use of this. }
16. h5 { Ok, let's advance further to create some pressure on the Kingside. }
16... Bd7
{ 16...h6  was clearly required from Black, in order to stop us from further expanding and dampening his dark squares as happened in the game. Play might have continued with the typical Rook shift  17.Rh3  followed by b4! at some point, totally sealing Black's play on the Queenside. Next we would play g4, creating some threats against the h6 pawn push. Though Black is worse, he is not lost and he can hope to survive, but after the move 16...Bd7 played in the game, he is busted. }
17. h6
{ And now White's pawn on h6 is super annoying, which is not only reflected in the middle game but also in the endgame as you can witness in this game. Allowing White to advance with h6 was a positional blunder from the Black side. }
17... g6 18. b4
{ This move is quite typical and has to be noted. And now the c5 Knight has no proper squares. }
18... Na4
{ 18...Nb7  is met by stunning tactics:  19.Nxd5  exd5  20.e6  and now you can see how annoying the pawn on h6 is as we threaten Qg7 mate.  20...f6  21.exd7  Qxd7  22.Qxd5  and we have an extra pawn with a winning position. }
19. Nxa4 bxa4 20. Bxa6 { Thank you for the pawn. :@@EndBracket@@ } 20... Bb5
21. Bxb5 Rxb5 { Black's only hope is to bring the Rook on c8 to c4 somehow. }
22. Rh3
{ Once again as you see quite often, in these structures once we have played h4, this Rook shift is always useful and protects the Queenside from a distance. }
22... Rc8 23. Rd2 Rb6
{ Black is preparing for Rc6-Rc4 and if he gets a nice outpost there, he will clearly obtain nice compensation for the pawn. However, here comes a mind-blowing and jaw-dropping masterpiece move. One of the best moves I have ever played in my whole chess career so far. }
24. c4
{ Bam! A positional killer. It reminds me of this fascinating game which happened recently between Richard Rapport and Caruana in GCT, Paris Rapid and Blitz 2021 where Rapport unleashed the move of the year with 36. d4!! moving his pawn to an unprotected square controlled by six enemies! Do check this game out. I was spellbound. :@@EndBracket@@ And similarly 24. c4 is the same story here. We give up the pawn to open the d-file or the c-file. And in fact this is the strongest move here and the top choice of Stockfish. So I was really proud of this move after the game. }
24... Qxc4+
{ 24...Rc6  25.c5  is dead for Black,   and if  24...dxc4  we gain full control over the d-file with  25.Qd7  and if  25...Qb8  26.Qe7  & Qf6 is game over. }
25. Qxc4 Rxc4+
{ 25...dxc4  26.Rd7  is devastating as well as we occupy the seventh rank and Black's Rooks are passive, lack activity and his pawns on c4 and a4 are also scattered and vulnerable. }
26. Rc2
{ Finally, thanks to this pawn sacrifice we have opened up the c-file and we also have a passed pawn on b4. Black's King is too far away and that clearly helps us. }
26... Rbc6
{ 26...Rxc2  27.Kxc2  Rc6  28.Rc3  and the pawn ending is winning as after  28...Rxc3  29.Kxc3  we follow up with b5-Kb4-Kxa4. }
27. Rxc4 Rxc4+ 28. Kb2
{ Next on the agenda is Rc3 and now you can also see that even in the endgame this pawn on h6 is annoying as it restricts the King totally. }
28... Kf8 { Trying to bring the King closer. } 29. Rc3
{ Our main goal is to seek entry into the c-file and penetrate. } 29... Rxf4
30. b5 { Now it's time to push. } 30... Ke8
{ If  30...Rf2  there is  31.Rc2  and if  31...Rxc2  32.Kxc2  the endgame is once again winning for White as we have Kc3-Kb4-Kxa4 and we have connected passed pawns. }
31. b6
{ The pawn needs two more moves to reach its destination. :@@EndBracket@@ }
31... Rf2+ 32. Kb1
{ 32.Rc2  now would be a blunder due to  32...Rxc2  33.Kxc2  Kd7  and ...Kc6 and the b6 pawn falls. Placing the King on b1 rather than on c1 has a deep subtle point. Once we deal with the lines, you guys will come to understand the whole point. }
32... Rf1+
{ 32...Kd8  33.b7  Rf1+  34.Kc2  Rf2+  35.Kd3  Rb2  36.Rc8+  wins.   And if  32...Kd7  then  33.Rc1!!  is the ethreal point behind Kb1 as now the b-pawn is unstoppable. }
33. Kc2 Kd7 34. Rc7+
{ Rook on seven is heaven. :@@EndBracket@@  The golden Quote which I have used quite often in my courses.   34.b7  is a blunder as Black gets a perpetual with  37...Rf2+  . }
34... Kd8 35. Kd3
{ Now the King is also joining the party as the Rook on f1 is tied down to the protection of the f7 pawn. }
35... Rf2 36. Ke3 Rf1 37. Ke2 Rh1
{ 37...Rf5  is met by either  38.Rc1  or  38.Rc5  and the b-pawn is unstoppable. }
38. Rxf7 { Now it's all over. } 38... Kc8 39. Rxh7 Kb8 40. Kd3 Rd1+ 41. Kc2 Rh1
42. Kc3 Rh4 43. g3 Rg4 44. Rf7
{ And my opponent resigned here. A clean and smooth win by me and I was extremely proud of this game which goes into my best game collections. :@@EndBracket@@ One can witness so many typical ideas and plans in the French from this duel. And it was also so pleasant for me to revisit this epic game. :@@EndBracket@@ }
